To implement a simplified version of Git called "minigit" in C, we will create a basic version control system that can handle a few essential commands. Below is a simple implementation along with a Makefile to compile the program.

### Directory Structure
```
minigit/
├── Makefile
├── minigit.c
└── test-v1.sh
```

### minigit.c
Here is a basic implementation of `minigit` in C:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/stat.h>
#include <dirent.h>

#define MAX_FILES 100
#define MAX_FILENAME_LENGTH 256

void init() {
    mkdir(".minigit", 0777);
    printf("Initialized empty minigit repository in .minigit\n");
}

void add(const char *filename) {
    struct stat buffer;
    if (stat(filename, &buffer) != 0) {
        printf("Error: File '%s' does not exist.\n", filename);
        return;
    }

    FILE *src = fopen(filename, "r");
    if (!src) {
        printf("Error: Could not open file '%s'.\n", filename);
        return;
    }

    char dest_filename[MAX_FILENAME_LENGTH];
    snprintf(dest_filename, sizeof(dest_filename), ".minigit/%s", filename);
    FILE *dest = fopen(dest_filename, "w");
    if (!dest) {
        printf("Error: Could not create file in .minigit.\n");
        fclose(src);
        return;
    }

    char ch;
    while ((ch = fgetc(src)) != EOF) {
        fputc(ch, dest);
    }

    fclose(src);
    fclose(dest);
    printf("Added '%s' to the minigit repository.\n", filename);
}

void status() {
    DIR *dir = opendir(".minigit");
    struct dirent *entry;
    printf("Tracked files:\n");
    while ((entry = readdir(dir)) != NULL) {
        if (entry->d_name[0] != '.') {
            printf(" - %s\n", entry->d_name);
        }
    }
    closedir(dir);
}

void commit(const char *message) {
    if (message == NULL) {
        printf("Error: Commit message is required.\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("Committed with message: '%s'\n", message);
}

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    if (argc < 2) {
        printf("Usage: ./minigit <command> [<args>]\n");
        return 1;
    }

    if (strcmp(argv[1], "init") == 0) {
        init();
    } else if (strcmp(argv[1], "add") == 0 && argc == 3) {
        add(argv[2]);
    } else if (strcmp(argv[1], "status") == 0) {
        status();
    } else if (strcmp(argv[1], "commit") == 0 && argc == 3) {
        commit(argv[2]);
    } else {
        printf("Unknown command: %s\n", argv[1]);
        return 1;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

### Makefile
Here is a simple Makefile to compile the `minigit` program:

```Makefile
CC = gcc
CFLAGS = -Wall -Wextra -std=c11
TARGET = minigit

all: $(TARGET)

$(TARGET): minigit.c
	$(CC) $(CFLAGS) -o $(TARGET) minigit.c

clean:
	rm -f $(TARGET)
```

### test-v1.sh
You will need a test script to verify the functionality of your `minigit`. Below is a simple example of what that might look like:

```bash
#!/bin/bash

# Test initialization
./minigit init

# Test adding a file
echo "Hello, World!" > testfile.txt
./minigit add testfile.txt

# Test status
./minigit status

# Test commit
./minigit commit "Initial commit"

# Clean up
rm testfile.txt
```

### Instructions to Run
1. Create a directory named `minigit` and place the above files in it.
2. Open a terminal and navigate to the `minigit` directory.
3. Run `make` to compile the program.
4. Run `bash test-v1.sh` to execute the tests.

This implementation is a very basic version of a version control system and does not include many features of Git, but it serves as a starting point for understanding how such a system might be structured. You can expand upon this by adding more features like removing files, viewing commit history, etc.
